  "topic_id": "T02.01",
  "topic_name": "Structure of Chromosomes and DNA",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Chromosomes are thread-like structures in the nucleus made of DNA and proteins (histones). Each chromosome consists of two sister chromatids joined at the centromere. The ends of chromosomes are called telomeres. Chromosomes are classified based on centromere position: metacentric (middle), submetacentric (slightly off-center), acrocentric (near end), and telocentric (at end). Humans have 46 chromosomes (22 pairs of autosomes and 1 pair of sex chromosomes). DNA is a double helix composed of nucleotides, each containing a deoxyribose sugar, phosphate group, and a nitrogenous base. The bases are adenine (A), thymine (T), guanine (G), and cytosine (C), with A pairing with T and G pairing with C. Genes are segments of DNA that code for proteins. DNA replication is semi-conservative, meaning each new DNA molecule has one original and one new strand. RNA differs from DNA in having ribose sugar, uracil instead of thymine, and being single-stranded.",
    "rules": [
      "Chromosome = DNA + histone proteins",
      "Centromere joins sister chromatids; telomeres cap chromosome ends",
      "Humans: 46 chromosomes = 44 autosomes + 2 sex chromosomes",
      "DNA double helix discovered by Watson and Crick",
      "Nucleotide = sugar + phosphate + nitrogenous base",
      "Base pairing: A-T (2 H bonds), G-C (3 H bonds)",
      "Gene = functional unit of heredity",
      "DNA replication is semi-conservative",
      "RNA types: mRNA (messenger), tRNA (transfer), rRNA (ribosomal)"
    ]
  },
